<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1844,2013]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1844,1869]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Vilkamaa &amp; Suuronen, 2019" authorityName="Vilkamaa &amp; Suuronen" authorityYear="2019" box="[339,518,1844,1868]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Bradysia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="torosa" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[339,518,1844,1868]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Bradysia torosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[525,589,1844,1869]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[525,589,1844,1869]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs in some characters from the other species of the group (dark colour, large size, shorter wing vein c) but shares with them the basic structure of the hypopygium, including the dorsally excavated gonostylus, sclerotized medial structures of tegmen, long apodemes of gonocoxa and of tegmen, and we place it tentatively to this group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1257,1988,2013]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1844,2013]" box="[199,1257,1988,2013]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1988,2013]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is Latin, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilkamaa &amp; Suuronen" authorityYear="2019" box="[557,628,1989,2012]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Bradysia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="torosa">
<emphasis box="[557,628,1989,2012]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">torosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, muscular, referring to the robust habitus of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
